        <h2>Therapist Quality</h2>
        <p>Both platforms require therapists to be licensed in their respective countries. For Australian users, both claim to have Australian-licensed psychologists and therapists.</p>
        <p>In practice:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>BetterHelp</strong> has a larger therapist network globally, which means more choice when you're being matched. You can also specify preferences for gender, specialty, and communication style.</li>
          <li><strong>Talkspace</strong> has a slightly smaller network, which some users report leads to slower initial matching — but the therapists are generally reported as responsive.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Both platforms allow you to switch therapists at any time. BetterHelp's switching process is reportedly smoother.</p>

        <h2>Features That Matter</h2>
        <p><strong>Messaging:</strong> BetterHelp wins here. Their "unlimited" messaging genuinely means you can message your therapist whenever — and they typically respond once or twice a day. Talkspace's lower tiers cap messages at 5 per month on some plans, which isn't truly unlimited.</p>
        <p><strong>Video sessions:</strong> Roughly equal. Both offer video on their mid-to-premium plans. BetterHelp gives you 4 video sessions per month on their top tier; Talkspace gives you 2 live video sessions per month on comparable plans.</p>
        <p><strong>Phone calls:</strong> BetterHelp is the only one of the two that offers live phone sessions. If you prefer talking over typing or video, this is a point in BetterHelp's favour.</p>

        <h2>The Affiliate Side</h2>
        <p>If you've found this site via one of our links, you should know: Carevues is an affiliate partner of both BetterHelp and Talkspace. We earn a commission when you sign up — but it doesn't change our reviews or recommendations.</p>
        <p>Our honest view: BetterHelp's 40% recurring commission is significantly better for us as a publisher, but that also reflects the higher average subscription value on their platform. If you're a user, the extra features — unlimited messaging, phone sessions, more therapist choice — justify the slightly higher starting price.</p>

        <h2>Who Should Choose What?</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose BetterHelp if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>You want genuine unlimited messaging, not a capped plan</li>
          <li>You prefer to have the option for phone sessions</li>
          <li>You want more therapist choice during matching</li>
          <li>You're comfortable spending $60-100/week for more flexibility</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Talkspace if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Budget is your primary concern and you're comfortable on a text-only plan</li>
          <li>You've used Talkspace before and had a good experience</li>
          <li>You want the slightly lower entry price point</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Our Verdict for Australians</h2>
        <p><strong>BetterHelp wins for most people.</strong></p>
        <p>The combination of genuinely unlimited messaging, phone session options, and a larger therapist network makes it the more complete platform. The 40% price difference between the lowest tiers is real — but BetterHelp's base plan actually delivers more.</p>
        <p>That said, if budget is genuinely tight and you're committed to a text-only approach, Talkspace is a legitimate option. Just make sure you read the plan details carefully so you're not surprised by message caps.</p>

